</div>
<p>The <b>barnacle goose</b> (<i>Branta leucopsis</i>) belongs to the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genus" title="Genus">genus</a> <i>Branta</i> of black <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goose" title="Goose">geese</a>, which contains <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Species" title="Species">species</a> with largely black <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plumage" title="Plumage">plumage</a>, distinguishing them from the grey <i><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anser_(genus)" title="Anser (genus)" class="mw-redirect">Anser</a></i> species. Despite its superficial similarity to the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brent_goose" title="Brent goose" class="mw-redirect">brent goose</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetics" title="Genetics">genetic</a> analysis has shown it is an eastern derivative of the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cackling_goose" title="Cackling goose">cackling goose</a> lineage.</p>
<p></p>
<div id="toc" class="toc">
<div id="toctitle">
